sec.p:
In practical terms, the thermotropic hydrogel used in a smart window needs to fulfil several requirements (Seeboth et al., 2000, Schneider & Seeboth, 2001, Resch & Wallner, 2009, Zhou et al., 2014, Allen et al., 2017):
High visible light transmittance (380–780 nm) (> 70%);
Near-room-temperature transition (between 25 and 35 °C);
Steep switching gradient (< 10 °C);
High reversibility and low hysteresis in the heating-cooling process;
High viscosity to distribute the internal hydrostatic pressure evenly in the interspace of a glazing unit and not to run out;
Non-toxic, non-freezing, stable against UV radiation;
Low cost and good scalability.
